{
  "doc_id": "59969",
  "text": "Parasite growth diverts a considerable amount of host resources that would otherwise be available for host maintenance and reproduction [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] ), so one possible explanation for variable relationships between parasite population growth and host health is that under some conditions, the conflict over limited resources is less severe [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] ) and hosts are better able to tolerate parasites [CITATION_5] ). This could arise if resource abundance varies [CITATION_6] ) or if some environmental conditions (e.g., temperature) change the rate of resource utilization. Despite ample evidence of genotype-by-environment effects on resistance to infection (reviewed in [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] , the possibility that environmental conditions can promote tolerance by shifting the relationship between parasite growth and host health has not been explored.",
